<subSubSection pageId="109" pageNumber="102" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="109.[113,1089,985,1586]" pageId="109" pageNumber="102">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[113,230,985,1009]" pageId="109" pageNumber="102">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Body 
<quantity box="[303,431,986,1010]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.3" metricValueMax="3.4" metricValueMin="3.2" pageId="109" pageNumber="102" unit="mm" value="3.3" valueMax="3.4" valueMin="3.2">3.2–3.4 mm</quantity>
long, ca. 1.9× as long as wide. Dorsum and antennae almost unicolor, brown. Elytra densely, irregularly and coarsely punctate. Median carina of mesoventrite low except for extremely projecting portion near transverse carina. Basal four tarsomeres of female pro- and mesotarsi expanded. Female abdominal sternite 8 with a spiculum ventrale.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="112" lastPageNumber="109" pageId="109" pageNumber="102" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="109.[113,1089,985,1586]" pageId="109" pageNumber="102">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[113,252,1145,1169]" pageId="109" pageNumber="102">Description.</emphasis>
Measurement of 
<typeStatus box="[440,538,1146,1170]" pageId="109" pageNumber="102">holotype</typeStatus>
: Body length 
<quantity box="[686,772,1146,1170]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.4" pageId="109" pageNumber="102" unit="mm" value="3.4">3.4 mm</quantity>
; head 
<quantity box="[840,935,1146,1170]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.0" pageId="109" pageNumber="102" unit="mm" value="0.6">0.60 mm</quantity>
long and 
<quantity metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.5" pageId="109" pageNumber="102" unit="mm" value="0.95">0.95 mm</quantity>
wide; pronotum 1.0 mm long and 
<quantity box="[525,606,1178,1202]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.6" pageId="109" pageNumber="102" unit="mm" value="1.6">1.6 mm</quantity>
wide; elytra 
<quantity box="[747,828,1178,1202]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.2" pageId="109" pageNumber="102" unit="mm" value="2.2">2.2 mm</quantity>
long and 
<quantity box="[934,1015,1178,1202]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.8" pageId="109" pageNumber="102" unit="mm" value="1.8">1.8 mm</quantity>
wide.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="109.[113,1089,985,1586]" pageId="109" pageNumber="102">Coloration. Dorsum shining and almost unicolor, brown; antennae almost unicolor, brown; legs brown; mesoventrite, metaventrite and abdominal ventrites brown.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="109.[113,1089,985,1586]" box="[144,667,1274,1298]" pageId="109" pageNumber="102">
Body 
<quantity box="[208,336,1274,1298]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.3" metricValueMax="3.4" metricValueMin="3.2" pageId="109" pageNumber="102" unit="mm" value="3.3" valueMax="3.4" valueMin="3.2">3.2–3.4 mm</quantity>
long, ca. 1.9× as long as wide.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="109.[113,1089,985,1586]" pageId="109" pageNumber="102">
Head ca. 1.5× as wide as long, ca. 0.62× as long as and 0.60× as wide as pronotum, distinctly and densely punctate, bearing some large punctures (
<figureCitation box="[731,828,1338,1362]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="110.[151,182,1155,1174]" captionTargetBox="[171,1107,224,1129]" captionTargetId="figure-134@110.[168,1110,219,1137]" captionTargetPageId="110" captionText="Fig. 70. Leiodes akiyamai sp. nov.A – body, dorsal view; B – ditto, lateral view; C – antenna; D – elytral punctures; E – mesoventrite, lateral view. Scale I: 1 mm for A and B; II: 0.5 mm for C; III: 0.5 mm for E." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4272609" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4272609/files/figure.png" pageId="109" pageNumber="102">Fig. 70A</figureCitation>
); antennomeres 1–3 each longer than wide; antennomeres 4 and 11 each about as long as wide; remaining antennomeres each wider than long; antennomere 11 oval (
<figureCitation box="[582,680,1402,1426]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="110.[151,182,1155,1174]" captionTargetBox="[171,1107,224,1129]" captionTargetId="figure-134@110.[168,1110,219,1137]" captionTargetPageId="110" captionText="Fig. 70. Leiodes akiyamai sp. nov.A – body, dorsal view; B – ditto, lateral view; C – antenna; D – elytral punctures; E – mesoventrite, lateral view. Scale I: 1 mm for A and B; II: 0.5 mm for C; III: 0.5 mm for E." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4272609" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4272609/files/figure.png" pageId="109" pageNumber="102">Fig. 70C</figureCitation>
); relative lengths of antennomeres 2 to 11 – 2.8: 4.3: 1.9: 1.8: 1.4: 2.8: 1.0: 3.4: 3.4: 5.1.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="109.[113,1089,985,1586]" pageId="109" pageNumber="102">
Pronotum ca. 1.6× as wide as long, ca. 0.46× as long as and ca. 0.87 as wide as elytra, widest near base, feebly sinuate at posterior margin, distinctly and densely punctate, punctation similar to that on head (
<figureCitation box="[366,466,1530,1554]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="110.[151,182,1155,1174]" captionTargetBox="[171,1107,224,1129]" captionTargetId="figure-134@110.[168,1110,219,1137]" captionTargetPageId="110" captionText="Fig. 70. Leiodes akiyamai sp. nov.A – body, dorsal view; B – ditto, lateral view; C – antenna; D – elytral punctures; E – mesoventrite, lateral view. Scale I: 1 mm for A and B; II: 0.5 mm for C; III: 0.5 mm for E." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4272609" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4272609/files/figure.png" pageId="109" pageNumber="102">Fig. 70A</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="109.[113,1089,985,1586]" box="[144,462,1562,1586]" pageId="109" pageNumber="102">Scutellum distinctly punctate.</paragraph>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4272609" ID-Zenodo-Dep="4272609" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4272609/files/figure.png" pageId="110" pageNumber="107" startId="110.[151,182,1155,1174]" targetBox="[171,1107,224,1129]" targetPageId="110">
<paragraph blockId="110.[151,1127,1155,1201]" pageId="110" pageNumber="107">
Fig. 70. 
<taxonomicName authority="Hoshina, 2012" authorityName="Hoshina" authorityYear="2012" box="[221,370,1156,1174]" class="Insecta" family="Leiodidae" genus="Leiodes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="110" pageNumber="107" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="akiyamai" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[221,370,1156,1174]" italics="true" pageId="110" pageNumber="107">Leiodes akiyamai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[375,441,1155,1174]" pageId="110" pageNumber="107" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
A – body, dorsal view; B – ditto, lateral view; C – antenna; D – elytral punctures; E – mesoventrite, lateral view. Scale I: 1 mm for A and B; II: 0.5 mm for C; III: 0.5 mm for E.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="110.[151,1127,1240,1584]" pageId="110" pageNumber="107">
Elytra ca. 1.2× as long as wide in dorsal view, widest ca. at basal 2/5 (
<figureCitation box="[969,1071,1240,1264]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="110.[151,182,1155,1174]" captionTargetBox="[171,1107,224,1129]" captionTargetId="figure-134@110.[168,1110,219,1137]" captionTargetPageId="110" captionText="Fig. 70. Leiodes akiyamai sp. nov.A – body, dorsal view; B – ditto, lateral view; C – antenna; D – elytral punctures; E – mesoventrite, lateral view. Scale I: 1 mm for A and B; II: 0.5 mm for C; III: 0.5 mm for E." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4272609" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4272609/files/figure.png" pageId="110" pageNumber="107">Fig. 70A</figureCitation>
), not transversely strigose, densely, irregularly and coarsely punctate (
<figureCitation box="[831,996,1272,1296]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="110.[151,182,1155,1174]" captionTargetBox="[171,1107,224,1129]" captionTargetId="figure-134@110.[168,1110,219,1137]" captionTargetPageId="110" captionText="Fig. 70. Leiodes akiyamai sp. nov.A – body, dorsal view; B – ditto, lateral view; C – antenna; D – elytral punctures; E – mesoventrite, lateral view. Scale I: 1 mm for A and B; II: 0.5 mm for C; III: 0.5 mm for E." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4272609" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4272609/files/figure.png" pageId="110" pageNumber="107">Figs. 70A, 70B</figureCitation>
); punctation of elytra consisting of punctures of various sizes (
<figureCitation box="[679,779,1304,1328]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="110.[151,182,1155,1174]" captionTargetBox="[171,1107,224,1129]" captionTargetId="figure-134@110.[168,1110,219,1137]" captionTargetPageId="110" captionText="Fig. 70. Leiodes akiyamai sp. nov.A – body, dorsal view; B – ditto, lateral view; C – antenna; D – elytral punctures; E – mesoventrite, lateral view. Scale I: 1 mm for A and B; II: 0.5 mm for C; III: 0.5 mm for E." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4272609" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4272609/files/figure.png" pageId="110" pageNumber="107">Fig. 70D</figureCitation>
); sutural stria very fine, reaching from apex to ca. apical 2/5 of elytral length.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="110.[151,1127,1240,1584]" box="[181,573,1368,1392]" pageId="110" pageNumber="107">Metathoracic wings fully developed.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="110.[151,1127,1240,1584]" pageId="110" pageNumber="107">
Mesoventrite strongly microreticulate, impunctate, and almost glabrous; median carina of mesoventrite with distinct hump near a transverse carina (
<figureCitation box="[779,878,1432,1456]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="110.[151,182,1155,1174]" captionTargetBox="[171,1107,224,1129]" captionTargetId="figure-134@110.[168,1110,219,1137]" captionTargetPageId="110" captionText="Fig. 70. Leiodes akiyamai sp. nov.A – body, dorsal view; B – ditto, lateral view; C – antenna; D – elytral punctures; E – mesoventrite, lateral view. Scale I: 1 mm for A and B; II: 0.5 mm for C; III: 0.5 mm for E." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4272609" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4272609/files/figure.png" pageId="110" pageNumber="107">Fig. 70E</figureCitation>
); metaventrite sparsely and finely pubescent, strongly microreticulate.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="110.[151,1127,1240,1584]" pageId="110" pageNumber="107">
All femora slender; protibiae gradually and feebly widening from base to apex (
<figureCitation box="[1017,1114,1496,1520]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="111.[114,145,1501,1520]" captionTargetBox="[147,1057,753,1482]" captionTargetId="figure-214@111.[140,1063,741,1489]" captionTargetPageId="111" captionText="Fig. 71. Leiodes akiyamai sp. nov. A – female fore leg, ventral view; B – female hind leg, ventral view; C – female protibia, dorsal view; D – female metafemur, dorsal view; E – female abdominal sternite 8; F – coxite and stylus. Scale I: 0.5 mm for A; II: 0.5 mm for B; III: 0.5 mm for C; IV: 0.5 mm for D; V: 0.2 mm for E, and 0.1 mm for F." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4272611" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4272611/files/figure.png" pageId="110" pageNumber="107">Fig. 71C</figureCitation>
); tarsomeres 1–4 of protarsi and mesotarsi expanded (
<figureCitation box="[695,792,1528,1552]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="111.[114,145,1501,1520]" captionTargetBox="[147,1057,753,1482]" captionTargetId="figure-214@111.[140,1063,741,1489]" captionTargetPageId="111" captionText="Fig. 71. Leiodes akiyamai sp. nov. A – female fore leg, ventral view; B – female hind leg, ventral view; C – female protibia, dorsal view; D – female metafemur, dorsal view; E – female abdominal sternite 8; F – coxite and stylus. Scale I: 0.5 mm for A; II: 0.5 mm for B; III: 0.5 mm for C; IV: 0.5 mm for D; V: 0.2 mm for E, and 0.1 mm for F." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4272611" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4272611/files/figure.png" pageId="110" pageNumber="107">Fig. 71A</figureCitation>
); metafemur with a small dorsal projection posteroapically (
<figureCitation box="[444,542,1560,1584]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="111.[114,145,1501,1520]" captionTargetBox="[147,1057,753,1482]" captionTargetId="figure-214@111.[140,1063,741,1489]" captionTargetPageId="111" captionText="Fig. 71. Leiodes akiyamai sp. nov. A – female fore leg, ventral view; B – female hind leg, ventral view; C – female protibia, dorsal view; D – female metafemur, dorsal view; E – female abdominal sternite 8; F – coxite and stylus. Scale I: 0.5 mm for A; II: 0.5 mm for B; III: 0.5 mm for C; IV: 0.5 mm for D; V: 0.2 mm for E, and 0.1 mm for F." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4272611" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4272611/files/figure.png" pageId="110" pageNumber="107">Fig. 71D</figureCitation>
); metatibiae almost straight (
<figureCitation box="[852,950,1560,1584]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="111.[114,145,1501,1520]" captionTargetBox="[147,1057,753,1482]" captionTargetId="figure-214@111.[140,1063,741,1489]" captionTargetPageId="111" captionText="Fig. 71. Leiodes akiyamai sp. nov. A – female fore leg, ventral view; B – female hind leg, ventral view; C – female protibia, dorsal view; D – female metafemur, dorsal view; E – female abdominal sternite 8; F – coxite and stylus. Scale I: 0.5 mm for A; II: 0.5 mm for B; III: 0.5 mm for C; IV: 0.5 mm for D; V: 0.2 mm for E, and 0.1 mm for F." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4272611" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4272611/files/figure.png" pageId="110" pageNumber="107">Fig. 71B</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="111.[113,1089,219,723]" pageId="111" pageNumber="104">
Abdominal sternite 8 with a spiculum ventrale at central point of anterior margin (
<figureCitation captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="111.[114,145,1501,1520]" captionTargetBox="[147,1057,753,1482]" captionTargetId="figure-214@111.[140,1063,741,1489]" captionTargetPageId="111" captionText="Fig. 71. Leiodes akiyamai sp. nov. A – female fore leg, ventral view; B – female hind leg, ventral view; C – female protibia, dorsal view; D – female metafemur, dorsal view; E – female abdominal sternite 8; F – coxite and stylus. Scale I: 0.5 mm for A; II: 0.5 mm for B; III: 0.5 mm for C; IV: 0.5 mm for D; V: 0.2 mm for E, and 0.1 mm for F." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4272611" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4272611/files/figure.png" pageId="111" pageNumber="104">Fig. 71E</figureCitation>
); coxites and stylus as in 
<figureCitation box="[432,523,251,276]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="111.[114,145,1501,1520]" captionTargetBox="[147,1057,753,1482]" captionTargetId="figure-214@111.[140,1063,741,1489]" captionTargetPageId="111" captionText="Fig. 71. Leiodes akiyamai sp. nov. A – female fore leg, ventral view; B – female hind leg, ventral view; C – female protibia, dorsal view; D – female metafemur, dorsal view; E – female abdominal sternite 8; F – coxite and stylus. Scale I: 0.5 mm for A; II: 0.5 mm for B; III: 0.5 mm for C; IV: 0.5 mm for D; V: 0.2 mm for E, and 0.1 mm for F." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4272611" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4272611/files/figure.png" pageId="111" pageNumber="104">
Fig. 
<specimenCount box="[481,523,252,276]" pageId="111" pageNumber="104" type="generic">71F</specimenCount>
</figureCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="111.[113,1089,219,723]" box="[144,326,282,308]" pageId="111" pageNumber="104">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[144,207,282,308]" pageId="111" pageNumber="104">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[144,200,282,307]" italics="true" pageId="111" pageNumber="104">Male</emphasis>
.
</emphasis>
Unknown.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="111.[113,1089,219,723]" pageId="111" pageNumber="104">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[113,351,315,339]" pageId="111" pageNumber="104">Diffrential diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName=": HATCH" authorityYear="1929" box="[356,439,317,340]" class="Insecta" family="Leiodidae" genus="Leiodes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="111" pageNumber="104" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[356,439,317,340]" italics="true" pageId="111" pageNumber="104">Leiodes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species are usually described on the basis of male specimens. However, the above female specimens differ substantially from all known 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": HATCH" authorityYear="1929" box="[929,1012,349,372]" class="Insecta" family="Leiodidae" genus="Leiodes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="111" pageNumber="104" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[929,1012,349,372]" italics="true" pageId="111" pageNumber="104">Leiodes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the characters mentioned below, allowing me to describe the new species even though its male remains unknown.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="111.[113,1089,219,723]" lastBlockId="112.[151,1127,219,435]" lastPageId="112" lastPageNumber="109" pageId="111" pageNumber="104">
<bibRefCitation author="DAFFNER H." box="[144,315,444,468]" pageId="111" pageNumber="104" pagination="9 - 163" refId="ref71760" refString="DAFFNER H. 1983: Revision der palarktischen Arten der Tribus Leiodini Leach (Coleoptera, Leiodidae). Folia Entomologica Hungarica 44 (2): 9 - 163." type="journal article" year="1983">DAFFNER (1983)</bibRefCitation>
considered the median carina of the mesoventrite as an important morphological character at the subgeneric level. 
<taxonomicName authority="Hoshina, 2012" authorityName="Hoshina" authorityYear="2012" box="[612,806,477,500]" class="Insecta" family="Leiodidae" genus="Leiodes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="111" pageNumber="104" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="akiyamai" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[612,806,477,500]" italics="true" pageId="111" pageNumber="104">Leiodes akiyamai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[814,901,476,499]" pageId="111" pageNumber="104" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
has a distinctive median carina (
<figureCitation box="[283,380,507,532]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="110.[151,182,1155,1174]" captionTargetBox="[171,1107,224,1129]" captionTargetId="figure-134@110.[168,1110,219,1137]" captionTargetPageId="110" captionText="Fig. 70. Leiodes akiyamai sp. nov.A – body, dorsal view; B – ditto, lateral view; C – antenna; D – elytral punctures; E – mesoventrite, lateral view. Scale I: 1 mm for A and B; II: 0.5 mm for C; III: 0.5 mm for E." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4272609" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4272609/files/figure.png" pageId="111" pageNumber="104">Fig. 70E</figureCitation>
) and can be therefore easily distinguished from all other species inhabiting 
<collectingCountry box="[232,294,540,563]" name="Japan" pageId="111" pageNumber="104">Japan</collectingCountry>
and neighbouring regions. Moreover, the female protarsi and mesotarsi of most of species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": HATCH" authorityYear="1929" box="[352,437,573,596]" class="Insecta" family="Leiodidae" genus="Leiodes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="111" pageNumber="104" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[352,437,573,596]" italics="true" pageId="111" pageNumber="104">Leiodes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are slender, whereas tarsomeres 1–4 of the pro- and mesotarsi are expanded in 
<taxonomicName authority="Hoshina, 2012" authorityName="Hoshina" authorityYear="2012" box="[349,478,605,628]" class="Insecta" family="Leiodidae" genus="Leiodes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="111" pageNumber="104" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="akiyamai" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[349,478,605,628]" italics="true" pageId="111" pageNumber="104">L. akiyamai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[485,570,604,627]" pageId="111" pageNumber="104" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
(
<figureCitation box="[585,687,603,628]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="111.[114,145,1501,1520]" captionTargetBox="[147,1057,753,1482]" captionTargetId="figure-214@111.[140,1063,741,1489]" captionTargetPageId="111" captionText="Fig. 71. Leiodes akiyamai sp. nov. A – female fore leg, ventral view; B – female hind leg, ventral view; C – female protibia, dorsal view; D – female metafemur, dorsal view; E – female abdominal sternite 8; F – coxite and stylus. Scale I: 0.5 mm for A; II: 0.5 mm for B; III: 0.5 mm for C; IV: 0.5 mm for D; V: 0.2 mm for E, and 0.1 mm for F." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4272611" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4272611/files/figure.png" pageId="111" pageNumber="104">Fig. 71A</figureCitation>
), as is generally the case in the male protarsi and mesotarsi of most species of 
<emphasis box="[591,684,637,660]" italics="true" pageId="111" pageNumber="104">
<taxonomicName authorityName=": HATCH" authorityYear="1929" box="[591,679,637,660]" class="Insecta" family="Leiodidae" genus="Leiodes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="111" pageNumber="104" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Leiodes</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
In this character, 
<taxonomicName authority="Hoshina, 2012" authorityName="Hoshina" authorityYear="2012" box="[893,1089,637,660]" class="Insecta" family="Leiodidae" genus="Leiodes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="111" pageNumber="104" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="akiyamai" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[893,1089,637,660]" italics="true" pageId="111" pageNumber="104">Leiodes akiyamai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[113,199,668,691]" pageId="111" pageNumber="104" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
is similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Svec, 1996" authorityName="Svec" authorityYear="1996" box="[346,569,666,692]" class="Insecta" family="Leiodidae" genus="Leiodes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="111" pageNumber="104" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="stocki">
<emphasis box="[346,440,669,692]" italics="true" pageId="111" pageNumber="104">L. stocki</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="SVEC Z." box="[447,569,666,691]" pageId="111" pageNumber="104" pagination="73 - 77" refId="ref74161" refString="SVEC Z. 1996: Leiodes stocki sp. n. with new faunistic records of Leiodini from the Caucasus and Central Asia (Coleoptera: Leiodidae). Acta Entomologica Slovenica 4: 73 - 77." type="journal article" year="1996">
Švec, 
<quantity box="[515,569,667,691]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.06984" pageId="111" pageNumber="104" unit="in" value="1996.0">1996</quantity>
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
in which the female protarsi and mesotarsi are also expanded, but can be separated from it by having a distinctive median carina of the mesoventrite and the metafemora feebly expanded posteroapically at the dorsal side (
<figureCitation captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="111.[114,145,1501,1520]" captionTargetBox="[147,1057,753,1482]" captionTargetId="figure-214@111.[140,1063,741,1489]" captionTargetPageId="111" captionText="Fig. 71. Leiodes akiyamai sp. nov. A – female fore leg, ventral view; B – female hind leg, ventral view; C – female protibia, dorsal view; D – female metafemur, dorsal view; E – female abdominal sternite 8; F – coxite and stylus. Scale I: 0.5 mm for A; II: 0.5 mm for B; III: 0.5 mm for C; IV: 0.5 mm for D; V: 0.2 mm for E, and 0.1 mm for F." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4272611" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4272611/files/figure.png" pageId="112" pageNumber="109">Fig. 71D</figureCitation>
). In contrast, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Svec" authorityYear="1996" box="[357,452,253,276]" class="Insecta" family="Leiodidae" genus="Leiodes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="112" pageNumber="109" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="stocki">
<emphasis box="[357,452,253,276]" italics="true" pageId="112" pageNumber="109">L. stocki</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a low median carina similar to that on 
<figureCitation box="[944,1039,251,275]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="38.[151,182,1544,1563]" captionTargetBox="[251,1026,769,1525]" captionTargetId="figure-252@38.[244,1031,760,1529]" captionTargetPageId="38" captionText="Fig. 16. Leiodes circinipes (Rye, 1873).A – body, dorsal view; B – ditto, lateral view; C – dorsal color; D – antenna; E – elytral punctures; F – mesoventrite, lateral view. Scale I: 1 mm for A and B; II: 0.5 mm for D; III: 0.5 mm for F." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4272501" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4272501/files/figure.png" pageId="112" pageNumber="109">Fig. 16F</figureCitation>
, and its metafemora are strongly expanded.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
